You are already thinking about this in a more industry-shaped way than you might realize. Your design doc is clearly aiming for separation of concerns, reproducibility, graceful failure, and user clarity, and your older Python submission shows the same instincts in a simpler form: menu loop, explicit user feedback, defensive input handling, and state held in Python containers. The main gap is not “can you program this,” it is “how do I stop this becoming one large script and turn it into a small service with clear boundaries.”

The biggest architectural point is this: for an industry-style solution, I would not make Playwright the primary integration unless your assignment explicitly wants browser automation. The Australian Business Register provides ABN Lookup web services for integrating ABN validation and ABN data into applications, and those services are specifically intended for application use. The public ABN Lookup site is for manual searching, while the web services require registration and an authentication GUID. That makes the web service the cleaner production path, and Playwright the “demonstrate browser automation” path.

So the first decision is really about assignment intent. If the marker wants to see browser automation and your reasoning around it, then keeping Playwright is valid. But frame it honestly: “I am using browser automation to satisfy the practical requirements of the submission, while noting that an official web service exists and would normally be preferred in production.” That is strong DevOps reasoning because it shows you can distinguish between a teaching exercise and an operational design. This kind of design tradeoff is exactly the sort of thinking that shows up in DevOps and cyber-adjacent assessment work: choosing the right integration point, reducing fragility, and documenting why.

On Playwright itself, your mental model is close, but I would tighten the terminology. “Playwright test” is the test-runner framing. For this tool, think instead in layers: user input goes to a lookup workflow, the workflow calls a browser automation adapter, the adapter returns structured data, then the app validates, stores, logs, and presents the result. Playwright is well suited to this because it auto-waits for actionable elements and includes debugging and tracing support, which helps with reliability and diagnosability.

On storage, SQLite is the right default for what you described. It is embedded, transactional, serverless, and very easy to package with a Python application and Docker image. MongoDB is useful when you genuinely need flexible document structures, large-scale horizontal growth, or multiple services consuming evolving schemas, but it adds another moving part and another operational dependency. For a single-user or light multi-user CLI/service that stores ABN queries and results, SQLite gives you simpler deployment, fewer failure modes, and better reproducibility.

I would only push you toward MongoDB if at least one of these becomes true: you want to store highly variable nested response documents with minimal schema discipline; you expect the project to become a web app with several containers/services around it; or the assignment specifically wants you to demonstrate a document database. Otherwise, Mongo is likely solving a future scaling problem you do not yet have. In your case, “simple, reproducible, and easy to explain to a marker” points to SQLite very strongly. That is also the more defensible operational choice for a student submission because the marker can run one container or one Python process without provisioning a separate database.

A good industry-appropriate structure for this would be something like this in concept, not code: an entry point, a CLI layer, a service layer, an adapter layer, a storage layer, and a logging/config layer. In practical terms, your instinct of “main as entry point, one module for ABN lookup, one for database, utils for shared helpers” is sound. I would just sharpen the boundaries a little. “main” should only start the app and wire dependencies together. The CLI should handle menus and prompts. The lookup service should own the workflow. The browser adapter should be the only place that knows Playwright. The repository or database module should be the only place that knows SQLite. That way, if you later switch from Playwright to the official ABR web service, most of the app does not change. That is a very industry pattern: isolate external dependencies behind interfaces or adapters.

Your old inventory script is a useful reference here because it shows exactly where the next growth step is. Right now, that script mixes UI, validation, state, persistence-like behavior, and report generation in one file using globals and shared lists. That was fine for that assessment, but it is also the boundary you have already run into yourself. You even note repeated logic, shared globals, and the need for better structure in your own comments. That makes it a perfect “before” example for explaining why this new tool should separate responsibilities earlier.

For the ABN data model, you do not need Mongo-style freeform storage just because the source is JSON-like. In SQLite, you can still store clean structured records. I would think in terms of three record types. First, a lookup request: what the user asked for, when, and by which input source. Second, a lookup result: ABN, entity name, entity type, status, timestamps, and source metadata. Third, an event log or audit trail: what happened during the run. That already gives you enough structure to query history, reproduce outcomes, and show clear reasoning in your documentation. If you want to preserve the raw source payload for troubleshooting, store it as a raw text/blob column alongside normalized fields rather than making it your primary storage model. That keeps the app explainable and operationally simple. This is the classic “normalize what you query, keep raw evidence for traceability” approach.

On logging, your instincts are good, but the key shift is this: logs are primarily for operators and developers, not end users. End users need friendly messages. Logs need factual, structured events. Python’s standard logging module is built for this and supports severity levels and flexible configuration.

For a tool like this, I would separate three things clearly. User-facing output should be plain-language status such as “ABN found,” “No record returned,” or “Lookup failed due to network issue.” Application logs should record operational facts like start time, requested ABN, browser launch, navigation success, selector timeout, parse failure, database write success, and runtime duration. Error details should capture enough context to debug but not dump irrelevant noise. This distinction matters a lot in industry because dumping stack traces or browser internals onto the user is poor UX, while hiding everything from logs makes support painful.

For scope, the most useful things to log here are the lookup ID or correlation ID, timestamp, requested ABN, mode used such as headless or visible, source used such as Playwright or web service, outcome status, elapsed time, and any recoverable error class. If browser automation remains in scope, also log high-value browser events: page reached, search submitted, result selector found, result selector missing, retry attempted, and trace path if debugging was enabled. Playwright’s debugging and tracing features support that operational style well.

What I would not log is equally important. Do not log everything the browser sees, full page dumps on every run, or noisy selector chatter in normal mode. Do not bury the user in technical detail. Keep a normal log level for day-to-day use and a debug mode for development. That is a standard operational pattern because excessive logging becomes its own usability and security problem. From a DevOps mindset, useful observability is selective and intentional.

If I map your current knowledge to the gaps you are trying to close, it looks like this. You already have the basics of control flow, menu-driven interaction, defensive input handling, and the instinct to separate files. The main gaps are service boundaries, dependency isolation, storage choice rationale, operational logging, configuration management, and packaging strategy. None of those require advanced Python. They require disciplined structure. That is good news, because structure is exactly what this assignment seems designed to showcase.

For your submission narrative, I would frame the architecture around four principles. First, reproducibility: fixed dependencies, container packaging, documented setup, deterministic outputs. Second, simplicity: minimal moving parts, SQLite over external DB, one clear entry point, one responsibility per module. Third, resilience: graceful handling of invalid ABNs, selector failures, timeouts, and storage errors. Fourth, empathy: user-friendly prompts, understandable failures, and a clear distinction between user messages and developer logs. Those are all strong industry values.

My concrete recommendation is this. Build version 1 around Python plus a CLI, a lookup service, a Playwright adapter only if browser automation is required, SQLite for persistence, Python logging for operational events, and Docker only after the app works locally. In your report, explicitly note that the ABR offers official web services and that a production redesign would likely replace the Playwright adapter with an API adapter. That gives you a clean migration story and shows mature architectural reasoning.

The shortest answer to your database question is: stick with SQLite unless your rubric or future scope clearly demands MongoDB. The shortest answer to your architecture question is: yes, separate entry point, workflow logic, database access, and shared utilities—but think in terms of responsibilities, not just files. The shortest answer to your logging question is: log operational facts for developers, present plain messages for users, and keep debug detail behind a higher log level.

